# Compact CSS style

Write all CSS in this project using compact selector blocks.

## Default — short rules (≤140 chars)

- One selector block per line: `selector{prop:value; prop:value;}`
- Put a space after each `;` between properties on the same line.
- `@media` blocks: media query on its own line; each nested rule on one line (or use long-rule block if over 140 chars); closing `}` on its own line.
- Comments stay on their own lines.
- `@import` in `main.css` stays one import per line.
- Optional blank line between unrelated rule groups in long files.

## Exception — `:root` variables

In [`02-variables.css`](src/asset/css/02-variables.css), one custom property per line:

```css
:root{
--background:#ffffff;
--foreground:#171717;
--accent:#0070f3;
}
```

- `:root{` on its own line; closing `}` on its own line.
- Each `--token:value;` on its own line.

## Exception — long rules (>140 chars)

When a rule exceeds **140 characters** total, use a block with wrapped properties (not one property per line):

```css
body{
    background:var(--background); color:var(--foreground); font-family:var(--font-sans);
    min-height:100vh; line-height:1.6;
}
```

- `selector{` on its own line.
- Properties indented with **4 spaces**; multiple properties per line, wrapping at ~140 chars per line.
- Closing `}` on its own line.

## Do not touch

- **Do not reformat or edit** [`src/asset/css/03-load-font.css`](src/asset/css/03-load-font.css) unless the user explicitly asks to change font loading. No formatting exceptions apply to that file — leave it exactly as-is.

## Examples

```css
.grid{display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(12, 1fr);}
.grid--pad-xs{padding:var(--space-xs);}
a{color:var(--accent); text-decoration:none;}

@media screen and (min-width: 768px){
.grid__col4{grid-column:span 4;}
}
```

## Do not

- Do not use Prettier-style formatting (one property per line for normal selectors).
- Do not modify `03-load-font.css` when reformatting or editing other CSS files.
- Do not collapse `:root` tokens onto one line or expand short rules unnecessarily.
